YUM! I did change it up a bit but this recipe is super good. I cooked the veggies (used cauliflower and a few brussels sprouts) in vegetable broth. I didn't have any scallions, so I used chives from my garden. I didn't have cracker, so I substituted with bread crumbs made from my homemade bread. I omitted the horseradish -- just didn't sound good to me. Great flavors and perfect for a cold, rainy November day.

Rating: 3
Here's what I did: made a veg stock, boiled the cauliflower in it until fork tender, separated the stems and florets, riced the florets, and finely chopped the stems to add a little texture. Sound a little elaborate? It probably was for a weekday dish, but having made a ton of casseroles with similar ingredients, I can say boiling the veg in stock added some complexity to the overall flavor. I was aiming for something grit-like in texture, and the added step of ricing the florets not only eliminated some of the moisture from the cauliflower that likely would have watered down the mixture, it did add a little textural contrast. For those wanting something a little more elevated or whatever, this might be the way to go for you. Maybe not. Maybe you eat foie five days a week. In which case, la di dah. Anyways, this is a pretty good and simple recipe overall, and probably endlessly tweakable. I would not say this is a replacement for mac and cheese exactly, but something like a mashed potato mac and cheese, starchy amalgam.

